# Add a provider

A **provider** is one AI backend you want Equerry to talk to — a local Ollama
server, an Anthropic account, an OpenAI-compatible endpoint, and so on. You create
a provider *profile* for each backend, and later you point Equerry's jobs at those
profiles through [Capability Slots](/docs/capability-slots).

Equerry never proxies your traffic. Requests go straight from your device to the
endpoint you configure, and your API keys are stored **encrypted** on the device —
never uploaded, never logged.

## Open the provider form

In the app, open the **Providers** screen. If you have not added one yet, tap
**"Add your first provider"**; otherwise use **Add provider**. The form adapts to
the provider type you choose, showing only the fields that type needs.

## The fields

- **Label** — a name for this profile, e.g. *"Home Ollama"* or *"Work Claude"*.
- **Type** — one of the four provider types below. Choosing a type prefills the
  sensible defaults for it.
- **Base URL** — the endpoint Equerry calls. It is prefilled per type and you can
  edit it (except for OpenRouter, whose URL is fixed).
- **API key** — required for the hosted providers; hidden entirely for Ollama.
  It is masked, with a reveal toggle. When editing an existing profile, leave it
  blank to keep the key you already saved.
- **Model** — the model id to use. Type it freely, or tap one of the preset chips
  shown for the selected type.

## Add Ollama (a good first provider)

Ollama is the most private option: it runs models **locally**, so nothing leaves
your own network, and it needs **no API key**. It is the recommended place to
start.

1. Set **Type** to **Ollama**. The key field disappears — Ollama runs locally, so
   no API key is required.
2. **Base URL** defaults to `http://localhost:11434`. On a phone, `localhost` means
   the phone itself, so if Ollama runs on your computer set this to that machine's
   address on your network, e.g. `http://192.168.1.20:11434`.
3. Pick a **Model** — preset chips include `llama3.2`, `qwen2.5`, `mistral`, and
   `phi3`. Use any model you have pulled in Ollama.
4. Give it a **Label** and save.

## The other provider types

The hosted types all need an **API key**, which you create in that provider's own
dashboard. Otherwise the form is the same shape.

- **Anthropic** — base URL `https://api.anthropic.com`; model presets include
  `claude-sonnet-4-6`, `claude-opus-4-8`, and `claude-haiku-4-5`.
- **OpenAI-compatible** — for OpenAI itself or any API-compatible server. There is
  no default base URL, so enter the endpoint yourself; model presets include
  `gpt-4o`, `gpt-4o-mini`, and `o3-mini`.
- **OpenRouter** — base URL is fixed at `https://openrouter.ai/api/v1` (not
  editable); model presets include `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6`, `openai/gpt-4o`,
  and `google/gemini-2.0-flash`.

## Where your keys live

API keys are held in Android's Keystore-backed encrypted storage, separate from
the rest of the profile. They are never written to logs and never leave the device
except in the requests you make to the provider you entered them for.

## Next

With at least one provider saved, the final step is routing a job to it —
[map it to a Capability Slot](/docs/capability-slots).
